article.headline: Rogers posts double-double in win
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Rodney Rogers finally played the way the New Jersey Nets knew he could. Filling in for suspended forward Kenyon Martin, Rogers had 18 points, a season-high 13 rebounds and six assists to lead the Nets over the Washington Wizards 115-103 Wednesday night. "We have been patiently waiting for him to play like he had in the past," Nets guard Jason Kidd said. "One thing about Rodney, he never gets too high or too low, even when he doesn't play up to his ability. He just goes out and plays the game. Tonight was something we had been waiting for for a while." So had Rogers, who played 37 minutes while starting for Martin, who was sitting out the second game of a suspension. Rogers came to the Nets last season with the reputation of being one of the best sixth men in the game. He never lived up to it, and this season he was benched for a time because his play was so poor. He made everyone forget that Wednesday, shooting 7-of-16 from the field in helping the Nets win for the eighth time in 10 games and the 14th time in their last 18. "It was a lot of fun," said Rogers, who had only two other double-digit games in his previous 23 games. "I was out there ripping and running all over the floor, jumping, getting rebounds and getting some baskets. I'm just glad it was a team effort and we got the win." His play evoked chants of "Rodney Rogers!" when he went to the bench in the second half. Richard Jefferson scored 30 points for the Nets, including a 41-foot, 3-point floater at the end of the third quarter. Kidd had 18 points, 13 assists and seven rebounds as New Jersey set a season high for points in beating former assistant Eddie Jordan and his banged up Wizards for the third time this season. Jordan didn't get to see the final 8:38 of the Wizards' season-high ninth straight road loss. He was ejected for arguing a non-call on a shot by Kwame Brown. Jordan got a technical in the third quarter for arguing another call. Jordan left the arena before the Wizards opened their locker room to reporters. "He thought it was a foul and Eddie went after it a little bit," Washington assistant coach Mike O'Koren said. Washington guard Brevin Knight said the Wizards (10-27) don't get a lot of respect from the officials. "We know that we are going to get hit and sometimes there might not be a call," Knight said. "We just have to complete the play." Larry Hughes and Knight had 13 points apiece for Washington, which also got 16 mostly garbage points from Steve Blake and 14 from Jared Jeffries. New Jersey blew the game open by closing the third quarter with a 22-8 spurt that featured Rogers, Kidd and Jefferson. Kidd and Jefferson got the roll started by combining on a pair of layups, the last coming on a spectacular behind-the-back pass by Kidd. Kidd, who had seven assists in the quarter, also set up a big slam dunk by Rogers, who had a spectacular game with Martin serving the second of a two-game suspension for a fight last week with Corey Maggette of the Clippers. Jefferson added two 3-pointers late in the run, including the buzzer beater that left everyone laughing. That gave the Nets a 20-point lead and allowed Kidd to spend the fourth quarter on the bench.

Game notes
Knight left late in the third quarter following a collision with Jefferson. ... Martin will return to the lineup Thursday. ... New Jersey has won eight straight at home against the Wizards. ... New Jersey has won four straight at home and nine of 10. ... Washington is 4-17 on the road.
